description.narrative:
1.1. Ministry of Higher Education of Afghanistan is supported with guidance in establishment of the outgoing mobility mechanism;
1.2. Initial guidelines on Risk Mitigation for international learning mobility of Afghan women developed, implemented and monitored; 
1.3. Selection committee created to govern and steer the selection and implementing process;
2.1.Scholarships to study in Kazakhstan and Uzbekistan are awarded to Afghan women in selected areas; 
2.2.Foundation training in languages and cultures of the host countries for potential applicants developed and implemented;
2.3.Employment skills development summer schools are organized;
3.1.Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs of Afghanistan and Ministry of Higher Education are supported in enhancing women's employability upon return;
3.2.Practical activities to support women’s job applications and recruitment by public and private sector employers; 
3.3. Study tour for the responsible authorities to Kazakhstan to learn about the established national system of education and employability (Bolashak International Scholarship);

comment.narrative:
1. 30 Afghan women selected as the scholarship winners (10 Masters, 10 Bachelor’s, and 10 TVET). More (20) TVET learners will be selected in 2020, including 10 students in Kazakhstan and 10 students in Uzbekistan;

2.The first cohort of Afghan women arrived in Almaty on 14th of October 2019. Students took a week-long introductory course at Almaty Management University, where they learned about the program of the training, had a tour around the campus and gained an understanding about the conditions of the University, as well as the cultural peculiarities of Kazakhstan. They have an 8 month-long course of in-depth study of English language with further admission to the bachelors, masters and technical programs in Kazakhstani universities.
In the course of the year, two key events were held within the framework of the project, namely, the Welcome reception and the Official Launch of the project. Both events were organized with the participation of media representatives, and corresponding press and web releases were published on official web sources. In parallel, two short video films have been created during the year. The first one describes the initial stage of the project implementation, which includes such key parts as the arrival of Afghan women in Kazakhstan, familiarization with the university campus, as well as the scenes from the Welcoming reception in honor of the start of the educational programme. The second video illustrates a daily life of project participants and shows the scenes of how students spend their spare time in the student’s house and at the university.

1.1. Arranging logistics, visa, travel, dormitory and other registration formalities for selected candidates;
1.2. Organizing arrival, accommodation and start of the training process for 10 participants of the TVET Program in the field of Agronomy in compliance with the national quarantine measures of Uzbekistan; 
1.3. Jointly with UN Women conduct preparatory work for organizing a Winter School for the TVET Program participants. The purpose of the school is to adapt women to new conditions in the labor market and improve their leadership skills, which will allow them to be more competitive in the local labor market of Afghanistan;
1.4. 10 Afghan students graduated from Uzbek language program; 
1.5. Completed Orientation to TVET Programme on agronomy (accompanied by the basic subjects, as Mathematics, English, History, Biology, Chemistry, Physics);
1.6. Provision of multiple technical, educational, expert and analytical work for efficient delivery of Technical and Vocational Education and Training (TVET) for 10 Afghan women in the field of Agronomy;
1.7. Creating conditions for Afghan women to study subjects aimed at developing students leadership qualities and their skills in working in the digital economy (fundamentals of pedagogy and psychology, public speaking, digital economy, e-commerce, etc.);
1.8. Together with the UNDP Uzbekistan Communications Analyst, preparations are underway for conducting interviews with the TVET Program participants, where they can share more details about themselves, their family, and work. The interviews with the program participants will be periodically published in the media under the overall heading 10 Afghan Women Seeking to Change Their Future ;
1.9. Regular consultations meetings and monitoring of progress with national partners, UNDP Kazakhstan and UNDP Afghanistan offices as well EUD and Embassy of Afghanistan in Tashkent.

1.1. The arrival of 10 selected Afghan students to Tashkent was organized on 4 December 2020, including all logistical and visa issues were resolved; Students are accommodated in the dormitory of the Tashkent State Agrarian University and registered with the Ministry of Internal Affairs;
1.2. The arrival and accommodation of 10 participants of the TVET Program in the field of agronomy at the Tashkent State Agrarian University was organized; On December 28, 2020, the educational process began, in compliance with the national quarantine measures of Uzbekistan;
1.3. Together with UN Women, in February and June 2021, Winter and Summer Schools were held for participants in the TVET Program. The goal of the school is to adapt women to new conditions in the labor market and improve their leadership qualities, business skills, which will allow them to be more competitive in the local Afghan labor market;
1.4. 10 Afghan students completed the Uzbek language program;
1.5. 10 Afghan students completed the the TVET orientation program in agronomy, which was accompanied by basic subjects such as mathematics, English, history, biology, chemistry, physics; Students learned how to drive a car;
1.6. Starting in September 2021, 10 female students are provided with comprehensive technical, educational, expert and analytical work to effectively deliver technical and vocational education and training (TVET) in the field of agronomy;
1.7. At the Tashkent State Agrarian University, conditions have been created for the study by Afghan women of subjects aimed at developing students leadership qualities and skills in working in a digital economy (fundamentals of pedagogy and psychology, oratory, digital economy, e-commerce, etc.);
1.8. Together with the UNDP Communications Analyst in Uzbekistan, interviews with TVET Program participants were published, where they spoke in detail about themselves, their families and work. Interviews with participants in the program were periodically published in the media under the general headline 10 Afghan women seeking to change their future ;
1.9. There were constant consultations and monitoring of progress with national partners, UNDP offices in Kazakhstan and Afghanistan, as well as EUD and the Embassy of Afghanistan in Tashkent.

